[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Open Sicilian Introduction"]
[Black "The Open Sicilian Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ This is known as the Sicilian Defense. It is one of the most respected openings that Black can play and the currently the most popular response to 1.e4. Black wants to control the center, but does so with his c-pawn instead of his e-pawn. }
2. Nf3 { White develops normally controlling the e5 and d4 squares. } 2... d6
{ This is one of many moves that Black can try, all of of which are covered in this repertoire. }
3. d4
{ 3.D4 signifies the Open Sicilian and is the most effective way to play in this position. }
3... cxd4
{ If Black tries 3.Nf6 instead, the position transposes after 4.Nc3 cxd4. } 4.
Nxd4
{ The position has already become inbalanced. White's major advantage is that he has faster and easier development and can use this to put pressure on Black. Black's advantage is that he has acquired a central pawn majority and will be able to use the semi-open c-file in the future to attack White's king. Overall, White's position is a bit easier to play because his development advantage can quickly become very dangerous for Black. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 { White develops another piece and defends the pawn on e4. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Najdorf Variation: English Attack"]
[Black "English Attack: Transposition to Main Line after 7.Be7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ This is known as the Najdorf Sicilian. It has become the most popular and well-respected of the the sicilians and plays a key role in the repertoire of almost every top player. It has been popularized most notably by players like Bobby Fischer, Garry Kasparov, and Viswanathan Anand. Black's idea is to control the b5-square so that if he chooses to play e5, White cannot play Bb5+. a6 also proves to be a useful move in the long run because it supports a b7-b5 pawn push. However, the Najdorf can be beaten. }
6. Be3
{ This is one of three extremely popular ways to combat the Najdorf: 6.Be3 6.Bg5 and 6.h3. I have selected the English Attack because it is not excessively theoretical, but offers White very interesting attacking chances. }
6... e5
{ e5 is a key Najdorf move. Black does weaken the d5-square and create a backward pawn on d6. However, the d6-pawn is well-guarded and the hole on d5 is controlled by both the knight on f6 and later the light-squared bishop. Black hopes to later play the freeing move d5, which opens up his bishops and rids him of his weaknesses. }
7. Nb3
{ White brings his knight to safety. Nf3 is also playable, but it leads to more positional waters rather than exciting dynamic chess. }
7... Be7
{ Black chooses to develop dark-squared bishop before his light-squared bishop. It does not matter in which order Black develops the bishops. The position will quickly transpose back to the Main Line. }
8. f3
{ White prevents any Ng4 ideas and lends his e4-pawn some support. He will look to play Qd2 and castle long next. The pawn on f3 also prepares a g2-g4 push. }
8... Be6
{ Black develops his light-squared bishop to the standard e6-square. We are now back in the Main Line. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Najdorf Variation: English Attack"]
[Black "English Attack: Early Nbd7 with 9.b5 Transposition to Main Line"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ This is known as the Najdorf Sicilian. It has become the most popular and well-respected of the the sicilians and plays a key role in the repertoire of almost every top player. It has been popularized most notably by players like Bobby Fischer, Garry Kasparov, and Viswanathan Anand. Black's idea is to control the b5-square so that if he chooses to play e5, White cannot play Bb5+. a6 also proves to be a useful move in the long run because it supports a b7-b5 pawn push. However, the Najdorf can be beaten. }
6. Be3
{ This is one of three extremely popular ways to combat the Najdorf: 6.Be3 6.Bg5 and 6.h3. I have selected the English Attack because it is not excessively theoretical, but offers White very interesting attacking chances. }
6... e5
{ e5 is a key Najdorf move. Black does weaken the d5-square and create a backward pawn on d6. However, the d6-pawn is well-guarded and the hole on d5 is controlled by both the knight on f6 and later the light-squared bishop. Black hopes to later play the freeing move d5, which opens up his bishops and rids him of his weaknesses. }
7. Nb3
{ White brings his knight to safety. Nf3 is also playable, but it leads to more positional waters rather than exciting dynamic chess. }
7... Be6
{ Black develops his light-squared bishop to the standard e6-square. He controls the important d5-square and points his bishop at the queenside. }
8. f3
{ White prevents any Ng4 ideas and lends his e4-pawn some support. He will look to play Qd2 and castle long next. The pawn on f3 also prepares a g2-g4 push. }
8... Nbd7
{ One of the main ideas in this line of the English Attack for Black is to develop his queenside pieces with ...Nbd7 and then start a queenside attack with ...b5. }
9. Qd2
{ White's setup in the English Attack remains the same in many variations. Qd2 allows White to get his king out of the center with 0-0-0. }
9... b5
{ Black will start his attack on the queenside immediately with ...b5. Black's pieces aren't developed and his king isn't safe in the center. We might be able to take advantage of these factors if Black plays incorrectly. }
10. O-O-O
{ White brings his king to safety and prevents any ideas of ...d5 which opens up the center. }
10... Be7
{ Black will start developing his pieces to allow his king to castle.This line will transpose to one of the main lines. }
11. g4
{ While white is already developed and black isn't, White can use this time to initialize his own attack against Black's king on the kingside. }
*

