1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ This is known as the Najdorf Sicilian. It has become the most popular and well-respected of the the sicilians and plays a key role in the repertoire of almost every top player. It has been popularized most notably by players like Bobby Fischer, Garry Kasparov, and Viswanathan Anand. Black's idea is to control the b5-square so that if he chooses to play e5, White cannot play Bb5+. a6 also proves to be a useful move in the long run because it supports a b7-b5 pawn push. However, the Najdorf can be beaten. }
6. Be3
{ This is one of three extremely popular ways to combat the Najdorf: 6.Be3 6.Bg5 and 6.h3. I have selected the English Attack because it is not excessively theoretical, but offers White very interesting attacking chances. }
6... e5
{ e5 is a key Najdorf move. Black does weaken the d5-square and create a backward pawn on d6. However, the d6-pawn is well-guarded and the hole on d5 is controlled by both the knight on f6 and later the light-squared bishop. Black hopes to later play the freeing move d5, which opens up his bishops and rids him of his weaknesses. }
7. Nb3
{ White brings his knight to safety. Nf3 is also playable, but it leads to more positional waters rather than exciting dynamic chess. }
7... Be6
{ Black develops his light-squared bishop to the standard e6-square. He controls the important d5-square and points his bishop at the queenside. }
8. f3
{ White prevents any Ng4 ideas and lends his e4-pawn some support. He will look to play Qd2 and castle long next. The pawn on f3 also prepares a g2-g4 push. }
8... Nbd7
{ One of the main ideas in this line of the English Attack for Black is to develop his queenside pieces with ...Nbd7 and then start a queenside attack with ...b5. }
9. Qd2
{ White's setup in the English Attack remains the same in many variations. Qd2 allows White to get his king out of the center with 0-0-0. }
9... h5 10. O-O-O
{ The setup for White is usually the same. The idea behind 0-0-0 is not only to provide safety for the king but failure to do so will allow Black to get his pawn break...d5 in which will become a pest for White. }
10... Rc8
{ Black controls the semi-open c file. This is a crucial idea in all Sicilians because it allows Black to get some counterplay on this file.   * White must be wary of the ...Rxc3 exchange sacrifice which is a common theme for Black in these lines. }
11. Kb1
{ This is a prophylactic move that is very important in these positions. White takes his king out of the c- file while Black has control. This usually extracts the effectiveness of the Black's attack when the king was on c1. }
11... Be7
{ Black must develop his pieces before starting an all out attack on White's king because failure to do so will allow the weakness of his king safety to haunt him in the future. }
12. Bd3
{ White completes his development and can now start an effective kingside atttack. }
*

