1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ This is known as the Sicilian Najdorf. It is widely regarded as one of the most respected ways to play against 1. e4. Black's idea is to control the b5 square and later use his control of that square to play b5 himself. It has been championed by great players like Bobby Fischer, Garry Kasparov, and more currently, Maxime Vachier-Lagrave as well as other top players. }
6. Be3
{ This is one of three extremely popular ways to combat the Najdorf: 6. Be3 6. Bg5 and 6. h3. I have selected the English Attack because it is not excessively theoretical, but offers White very interesting attacking chances. }
6... Ng4
{ This is known as the anti-English. It has led to many draws after Bc1 Nf6 Be3 Ng4. However, White can play for a win with 7. Bg5. }
7. Bg5 h6 { Black hits the bishop. } 8. Bh4 g5
{ White continues to attack the bishop and frees the g7-square for his bishop, but weakens his kingside in the process. }
9. Bg3 Bg7 10. h3
{ White knocks the Black knight off of g4. Now Black has two squares to choose from for his knight. }
10... Ne5 { This is the more common choice. } 11. Nf5
{ White is letting Black double his pawns, but gains the bishop pair in return. }
11... Bxf5 12. exf5 Nbc6
{ Black brings his last piece into the game. He also has some alternatives. }
13. Nd5 { White's knight leaps to a strong central post. } 13... e6
{ Black tries to kick it away. } 14. fxe6 fxe6 15. Ne3
{ White's knight retreats after having created some extra pawn islands for Black to deal with. }
15... O-O { This is the main line. } 16. Be2 d5 17. O-O
{ White can try to undermine Black's pawns with h4. } 17... Ng6
{ Preventing h4. } 18. c4 { Now White is going for Black's central pawns. }
18... d4 19. Qc2 { White's position is fairly comfortable. } *

