[Black "Richter-Rauzer: Main Line 7.Be7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ This is known as the Classical Sicilian. It is still one of the most popular sicilians that Black can play. Black puts pressure on the center with his knight on c6. }
6. Bg5
{ This known as the Richter-Rauzer. It is the main line and gives White very good play. Now Black has many options. }
6... e6 { Black frees the e7-square for his bishop. } 7. Qd2
{ White will quickly play long castle and put pressure down the d-file. } 7...
Be7 { This is a very common alternative. } 8. O-O-O Nxd4
{ This knight trade leads to a long, forcing line. } 9. Qxd4 O-O 10. f4
{ White begins to push his pawns. } 10... Qa5 11. Bc4 Bd7
{ Black develops his bishop. } 12. e5
{ This is a critical move to be aware of. } 12... dxe5 13. fxe5 Bc6 14. Bd2
{ Now White can move his knight with tempo. } 14... Nd7 15. Nd5
{ with the gain of tempo. } 15... Qd8 { Qc5 transposes after Nxe7+ } 16. Nxe7+
Qxe7 17. Rhe1
{ This position has been reached hundreds of times. I don't think White needs to know any more theory here however because he can play with ideas in mind. White has the bishop pair and can attack Black's king by pushing his kingside pawns. I will nevertheless cover Black's two main moves. }
17... Nb6
{ This is Black's other main option. Black is simply threatening to get rid of White's bishop pair. }
18. Bf1 { This is a very nice move, protecting the g2-pawn. } 18... Rfd8 19.
Qg4 { Now White will start to create threats against Black's king. } 19... Rac8
20. Kb1 Qc5 21. Bd3
{ Now that g2 is protected, the bishop can comfortably land on d3. White has an advantage with the two bishops. }
*

