[Black "Richter-Rauzer: 6.Bd7 Sideline"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ This is known as the Classical Sicilian. It is still one of the most popular sicilians that Black can play. Black puts pressure on the center with his knight on c6. }
6. Bg5
{ This known as the Richter-Rauzer. It is the main line and gives White very good play. Now Black has many options. }
6... Bd7
{ This is another option that Black has. He wants to play an early Rc8. } 7.
Qd2 { White develops agressively. } 7... Rc8
{ Black uses the fact that he has freed the c8-square very early. } 8. f4
{ Since Black has not taken the time to develop his dark-squared bishop and castle, White should try to punish him with this aggressive move. }
8... Nxd4 { Black opens the c-file for his rook. } 9. Qxd4 Qa5
{ Black is trying to be as active as possible. } 10. e5
{ This is a very nice move that gives White excellent play. } 10... dxe5 11.
fxe5 e6
{ Black realizes that cxf6 can be met by Qxg4, when White does not have a significant advantage. }
12. O-O-O { White has strong pressure down the d-file. } 12... Bc6
{ This is Black's main idea, getting his bishop off of the dangerous d-file. }
13. Nb5
{ W  White takes advantage of the threats against the f6-knight and prepares to land on d6 with his knight. }
13... Bxb5 14. exf6 Bc6 15. h4 { White has a really nice advantage. } 15... g6
16. Bc4 { White develops harmoniously. } 16... Bc5 17. Qe5 Bxg2
{ This is a mistake. Now Black has too many problems. } 18. Bh6
{ This is a key move, preparing Bxe6. Black is best off giving back material. }
18... Be3+ 19. Qxe3 Rxc4 20. Qg3 Bd5 21. Qb8+ Qd8 22. Qxa7
{ White has won back the pawn with a nice advantage. } *

