{ The idea behind this move is to prevent Ng4 in the future, which would allow black to trade off White's useful e3-bishop. }
7... O-O 8. Qd2 { White continues to prepare to castle queenside. } 8... Nc6 9.
O-O-O
{ This is one of two main moves in this position. White's alternative is the 9. Bc4, which leads to an extremely sharp position. However, if Black is well-prepared, he will have excellent chances. The move 9. O-O-O is currently considered to be the more accurate approach. White seems to get a safe edge. }
9... d5
{ This is the main line. Black takes advantage of the fact that White did not control the d5-square with Bc4 on the last move. Now White can continue with a relatively forcing set of trades. }
10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bd4 { Here Black has a variety of options. }
12... e5
{ This is the main line and prepares an exchange sacrifice. However, White seems to have a much easier game. }
13. Bc5 { This is the most active square for the bishop. } 13... Be6
{ This is the renowned exchange sacrifice. Now White should decline the sacrifice to avoid giving Black too much play. }
14. Ne4 Rb8 { Black immediately places a rook on the semi-open b-file. } 15.
Bc4 f5 16. Ng5 e4 17. c3
{ White does not want to allow Black any play against the b2-pawn. } 17... Bh6
18. h4 { The position is very complex, but White has a clear edge. } *

