[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ This is known as the Scheveningen Variation of the Sicilian Defense. It has lost some popularity in past years due to the discovery of the Keres Attack, which scores excellently for White. Nevertheless, the Scheveningen Sicilian is still a dangerous weapon that should not be underestimated. }
6. g4
{ This is the Keres Attack. White immediately begins to attack Black on the kingside. It is the most critical and high-scoring line that White can play, but White has to feel comfortable sacrificing for an attack in many lines. If you are a more quiet player, you can try Be2, but it is not nearly as powerful. Now Black has many different options that he can try. }
6... h6 { This is the main line. } 7. h4
{ White continues to push his kingside pawns down the board. } 7... Nc6
{ This is Black's main developing move, but he certainly has other options. }
8. Rg1 { White is preparing g5. } 8... h5
{ This is the most popular line, trying to undermine White's pawns. } 9. gxh5
{ White should open the h-file. } 9... Nxh5 10. Bg5
{ White develops and attacks the queen. } 10... Nf6
{ Black brings his knight back. } 11. Be2 a6
{ Black needs to get some play of his own on the queenside. } 12. Qd2
{ White prepares to castle long. } 12... Qb6 13. Nb3 Bd7 14. h5
{ White sacrifices a pawn for his attack. Black has little choice but to accept the sacrifice. }
14... Nxh5 15. Rh1 g6
{ If Black moves the knight he will drop the rook on h8. } 16. O-O-O
{ White sacrifices yet another pawn! } 16... Qxf2
{ White is greedy and grabs the pawn. As a Keres Attack player it is very important to feel comfortable playing with dynamic compensation. If you can master that skill, you will quickly become a much stronger player. }
17. e5 { A strong move, blasting open the position. } 17... Nxe5
{ White takes the pawn. } 18. Ne4 *

