1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ This is known as the Scheveningen Variation of the Sicilian Defense. It has lost some popularity in past years due to the discovery of the Keres Attack, which scores excellently for White. Nevertheless, the Scheveningen Sicilian is still a dangerous weapon that should not be underestimated. }
6. g4
{ This is the Keres Attack. White immediately begins to attack Black on the kingside. It is the most critical and high-scoring line that White can play, but White has to feel comfortable sacrificing for an attack in many lines. If you are a more quiet player, you can try Be2, but it is not nearly as powerful. Now Black has many different options that he can try. }
6... e5
{ This is yet another option that Black has, but it seems a bit awkard as Black has lost some time moving his e-pawn twice. }
7. Bb5+ { White develops with tempo. } 7... Bd7 8. Bxd7+ Qxd7 9. Nf5
{ The knight has found a nice home on f5. } 9... h5
{ Black wants to undermine White's pawn on g4. } 10. gxh5
{ White can simply take, opening the g-file. Now Black has too choices. } 10...
Nxh5 { Black recaptures the pawn. Now White has a nice tactical idea. } 11. Bh6
g6 { gxh6 or Rxh6 followed by Nxh6 and then Qxh5 is much better for White. }
12. Bxf8 { White trades off a key defender of the d6-pawn. } 12... gxf5 13.
Bxd6 { White grabs as much material as he can. } 13... Nc6 14. Bc5 Qxd1+ 15.
Rxd1 { White has a clear edge in this endgame. } *

