[White "Sveshnikov Variation: Chelyabinsk Variation"]
[Black "Chelyabinsk Variation: Main Line 9.Qa5+ Sideline"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ Black puts immediate pressure on White's e4-pawn. } 5. Nc3 e5
{ Black finally puts a pawn in the center. The downside of this move is that it weakens the d6-square significantly and creates a backward pawn on the d-file. Black will have some dynamic compensation however. }
6. Ndb5 { White eyes the weak d6-square. } 6... d6
{ Black does not want to allow White to occupy the d6-square with his knight. }
7. Bg5
{ White is fighting for the d5-square. Bg5 indirectly pressures that square because the knight on f6 is a key defender of d5. By nullifying the knights control of d5, White will be able to occupy the square himself in the future. }
7... a6 { Black attacks the knight } 8. Na3 b5
{ Black continues to play very dynamically, but he is lagging behind in development. }
9. Nd5
{ This one of two main lines, the other being 9. Bxf6. I have chosen this move however because there has been a fairly recent theoretical development in this line that promises White a very nice position. }
9... Qa5+
{ This move is often played against unprepared opponents, but in reality it is somewhat dubious. }
10. Bd2 { Retreating the bishop and hitting th } 10... Qd8
{ The queen is forced to return as it really doesn't have a better square. }
11. Nxf6+
{ White plays for a win. He can also repeat moves with Bg5 if he would like. }
11... Qxf6 12. Bd3 { White has developed all of his pieces. } 12... Qg6
{ Black tries to create threats. } 13. O-O Be7 14. c4
{ This is a nice move breaking apart Black's connected pawns on the queenside. The position is complex. }
*

