{ Bg5 does not change White's plans. In fact it is likely to transpose back to the main line. }
14. Bg2
{ White has a nice position. The fianchetto is complete and Black has some weaknesses. }
14... O-O 15. O-O { White can play for a win with very little risk. } 15... Be6
{ Ne7 is covered in another variation. } 16. Qd3 Ne7 17. h4 Bh6 18. a3
{ White is hacking at Black's pawns. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Sveshnikov Variation: Chelyabinsk Variation"]
[Black "Chelyabinsk Variation: Main Line 12.a5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ Black puts immediate pressure on White's e4-pawn. } 5. Nc3 e5
{ Black finally puts a pawn in the center. The downside of this move is that it weakens the d6-square significantly and creates a backward pawn on the d-file. Black will have some dynamic compensation however. }
6. Ndb5 { White eyes the weak d6-square. } 6... d6
{ Black does not want to allow White to occupy the d6-square with his knight. }
7. Bg5
{ White is fighting for the d5-square. Bg5 indirectly pressures that square because the knight on f6 is a key defender of d5. By nullifying the knights control of d5, White will be able to occupy the square himself in the future. }
7... a6 { Black attacks the knight } 8. Na3 b5
{ Black continues to play very dynamically, but he is lagging behind in development. }
9. Nd5
{ This one of two main lines, the other being 9. Bxf6. I have chosen this move however because there has been a fairly recent theoretical development in this line that promises White a very nice position. }
9... Be7 { Black prepares to castle and breaks the pin on the f6-knight. } 10.
Bxf6
{ White is giving up his bishop pair for a greater cause: absolute control of the d5-square. }
10... Bxf6 11. c4
{ This is the new theoretical development that I mentioned earlier and is quickly becoming the new main line as White has excellent results in this position. The old main line is 11. c3 followed by Nc2 and Nce3. However, that promises Black good chances. }
11... b4 { This move is practically forced. } 12. Nc2
{ White retreats his knight. } 12... a5
{ Black supports his pawn on b5. This is the main move, but Black certainly has other options. }
13. g3
{ It is important to remember to fianchetto the light-squared bishop in this line. }
13... O-O 14. Bg2 Bg5 15. O-O Ne7
{ Black wants to get rid of the d5-knight. This is the main line. } 16. Nce3
Bxe3 { Black wants to get rid of White's dominating knights. } 17. Nxe3 Be6 18.
Qd3 Qc7 19. Rac1 { White is beginning to pile up on Black's weaknesses. } 19...
Rac8 20. Rfd1 Rfd8 21. b3 Nc6 22. Rd2
{ A nice move, preparing to triple on the d-file. Black will have to worry about his d6-pawn for the rest of the game. }
*

