{ This is the main line continuation. Black tries to give the d5-square some support with his bishop. }
9. Be2 { White prepares to castle. } 9... Nd4
{ This knight appears to be very strong but it will quickly be removed after... }
10. O-O Nf6 11. Be3 { White threatens Bxd4 } 11... Nxe2+ 12. Qxe2
{ Black has the bishop pair, but White's knight will become very annoying because they can bear down on the d5-square very conveniently. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Kalashnikov Variation: Maroczy Bind"]
[Black "Maroczy Bind: Main Line 8.f5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5
{ This is known as the Kalashnikov Sicilian. It is similar to the Sveshnikov Sicilian in many ways, but Black has not taken the time to play Nf6 before playing e5. This is an important difference. }
5. Nb5 { White's knight which has just been attacked heads for d6. } 5... d6
{ Black does not want to allow Nd6 so he prevents it by playing d6 himself. }
6. c4
{ This is a very strong way to play against the Kalshnikov. White creates a very firm grip of the d5-square. }
6... Be7 { Black has nothing better than to proceed with development. } 7. N1c3
a6 { Black kicks away the annoying knight on b5. } 8. Na3 f5
{ This is a very dynamic try, but White has a strong response. } 9. exf5 Bxf5
10. Bd3 { White offers a trade of bishops. } 10... Be6
{ Accepting the trade would leave Black's position very weak. } 11. O-O Nf6 12.
Nc2 { White's knight is heading for e3, were it eyes the d5-square. } 12... O-O
13. Ne3 Qd7 14. b3
{ Black has to deal with his backward d6-pawn and weak d5-square for the rest of the game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Kalashnikov Variation: Maroczy Bind"]
[Black "Maroczy Bind: Main Line 8.Be6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5
{ This is known as the Kalashnikov Sicilian. It is similar to the Sveshnikov Sicilian in many ways, but Black has not taken the time to play Nf6 before playing e5. This is an important difference. }
5. Nb5 { White's knight which has just been attacked heads for d6. } 5... d6
{ Black does not want to allow Nd6 so he prevents it by playing d6 himself. }
6. c4
{ This is a very strong way to play against the Kalshnikov. White creates a very firm grip of the d5-square. }
6... Be7 { Black has nothing better than to proceed with development. } 7. N1c3
a6 { Black kicks away the annoying knight on b5. } 8. Na3 Be6
{ This is the main line continuation. Black tries to give the d5-square some support with his bishop. }
9. Be2 { White prepares to castle. } 9... Bg5
{ Black wants to trade dark-squared bishops. } 10. O-O
{ White can simply castle. } 10... Bxc1 11. Rxc1
{ White's rook is now active. } 11... Nf6 { Black develops his last piece. }
12. Nc2
{ White's knight controls the d4-square for the time being so that Black's c6-knight cannot jump into d4. }
12... O-O 13. Qd2 Qb6 14. Rfd1
{ Almost all of White's pieces are well placed, so White enjoys a comfortable edge. Note that Qxb2 loses the queen due to 15. Rb1 and the queen doesn't have any safe squares. }
