1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6
{ This move characterizes the Accelerated Dragon. Black prepares to fianchetto his bishop without having played d6. Now White has a very powerful line at his disposal known as the Maroczy Bind. }
5. c4
{ This is known as the Maroczy Bind is part of the reason why the Acclerated Dragon is barely ever played at the top level. White clamps down on the d5-square which prevents any d5 break by Black, and prepares to use his space advantage to win the game. The resulting positions are very transpositional and can result from various move orders. }
5... Bg7 { This is the first of two main moves at Black's disposal. } 6. Be3
{ White defends the knight on d4. } 6... Nf6 7. Nc3 { Defending the e4-pawn. }
7... Ng4
{ This is a tricky move. Black uses tactics trade off some minor pieces with the idea that having less pieces on the board will make his space disadvantage less bothersome. }
8. Qxg4 { White does not want to give up the e3-bishop. } 8... Nxd4 9. Qd1 e5
{ Black protects the knight by pushing his e-pawn. He is making serious positional concessions however, including the weakening of the d5-square. }
10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O d6 12. Qd2
{ White finishes his development and connects his rooks. } 12... Be6 13. Rad1
{ White brings one of his rooks into play and will have long-lasting pressure against the pawn on d6. }
*

