[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Kan Variation: Maroczy Bind"]
[Black "Maroczy Bind: Main Line with 5.Nf6 6.Bb4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ This is one of three main ways for Black to play after Nf3. E6 gives Black a lot of flexibility to decide where he wants to place his dark-squared bishop. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ This is known as the Kan Sicilian. It is a very flexible opening the offers good chances for both sides. }
5. c4
{ This is a very powerful sideline that leads to a Maroczy Bind position. I got the idea of playing it when Magnus Carlsen played it against Vishy Anand in their 2014 World Championship Match. }
5... Nf6 { This is Black's most common choice. } 6. Nc3 Bb4
{ This is the second most popular move, pinning the c3-knight. } 7. Qd3
{ White prevents Black from doubling his c-pawns. } 7... d6
{ A playable move. } 8. Nc2 Bc5 9. b4
{ Demonstrating why Nc2 was useful. Now b4 can be played as the pawn is protected. }
9... Ba7 10. Be2 { White's position is fantastic. } *

