[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Paulsen and Taimanov Variations: Main Line"]
[Black "Main Line: 9.h5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ This is one of three main ways for Black to play after Nf3. E6 gives Black a lot of flexibility to decide where he wants to place his dark-squared bishop. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3
{ Now Black can decide whether he wants to play Qc7 or a6 to enter a Paulsen Sicilian. It is also known as a Taimanov Sicilian. Nf6 leads to a Four Knights Sicilian which is covered in another chapter. }
5... Qc7
{ This move order is much more common in modern times because Black avoids a very powerul idea. }
6. Be3 { This is one of many excellent lines that White can choose. } 6... a6
7. Qd2 { White is preparing to castle long. } 7... Nf6 8. O-O-O
{ White simply castles. } 8... Be7
{ This is the more conservative approach to the position. } 9. f3
{ White's position is fairly asy to play. He will be able to push his kingside pawns next and attack Black's king. }
9... h5 { This another move Black can try. } 10. Kb1
{ This is a nice little move, waiting to see if Black will try to castle. }
10... b5 11. Nxc6 dxc6 12. Qf2
{ Black has an uncomfortable position as c5 allows Qg3 when Black is forced to take on g3 and will have to defend for the rest of the game. }
*

