[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ This is one of three main ways for Black to play after Nf3. E6 gives Black a lot of flexibility to decide where he wants to place his dark-squared bishop. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3
{ Now Black can decide whether he wants to play Qc7 or a6 to enter a Paulsen Sicilian. It is also known as a Taimanov Sicilian. Nf6 leads to a Four Knights Sicilian which is covered in another chapter. }
5... Qc7
{ This move order is much more common in modern times because Black avoids a very powerul idea. }
6. Be3 { This is one of many excellent lines that White can choose. } 6... a6
7. Qd2 { White is preparing to castle long. } 7... Nf6 8. O-O-O
{ White simply castles. } 8... Bb4 { This is a more aggressive move than Be7. }
9. f3
{ f3 prevents any Ng4 ideas that would allow Black to trade off White's bishop on e3. }
9... Ne5 { Black's knight is heading for c4. } 10. Nb3
{ White clears the d-file. } 10... b5 11. Qe1
{ White's queen can now easily swing over to the kingside. } 11... Rb8
{ This is also playable. } 12. Qg3 { White brings his queen to the kingside. }
12... O-O { This is Black's first option. } 13. Bd4
{ White improves the position of the bishop and prevents Black from winning material on c3. }
13... Bd6 14. f4
{ Here White has a very cool idea. He will sacrifice his queen in favorable fashion. }
14... Nh5 15. fxe5 Nxg3 16. exd6 { White grabs as many pieces as he can. }
16... Qxd6 17. hxg3 Qxg3 18. Rh3 Qg5+ 19. Be3
{ Black has a material advantage. However, White has full compensation because all of his pieces can attack White's king. It is much easier to play White here than to have to defend with Black. }
*

