[White "Paulsen and Taimanov Variations: Main Line"]
[Black "Main Line: An early a6 with 5.a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ This is one of three main ways for Black to play after Nf3. E6 gives Black a lot of flexibility to decide where he wants to place his dark-squared bishop. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3
{ Now Black can decide whether he wants to play Qc7 or a6 to enter a Paulsen Sicilian. It is also known as a Taimanov Sicilian. Nf6 leads to a Four Knights Sicilian which is covered in another chapter. }
5... a6
{ This move order used to be quite popular until it was discovered that White can play Nxc6 to achieve a very good position. }
6. Nxc6 bxc6 { dxc6 Qxd8+ Kxd8 Bf4 is very unpleasant for Black. } 7. Bd3
{ Once the e4 pawn moves or is traded off, the bishop on d3 will become a very powerful piece. }
7... d5
{ Black takes advantage of the previous trade to create an impressive center. }
8. O-O { White simply castles. } 8... Nf6 9. Re1
{ This is a clever move. Once the e-file is opened the rook will become quite strong. }
9... Bb7 { Black's bishop feels a bit awkwardly placed on b7. } 10. Qf3 Be7 11.
Qg3
{ White is making quick threats. Black's position is relatively unpleasant. }
11... O-O 12. Bh6 Ne8 13. Bf4 { Black's position is a bit passive. } *

