[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Less Common Sicilians"]
[Black "Less Common Sicilians: Nimzowitsch Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ This quirky Sicilian is known as the Nimzowitsch Variation. Black allows White to play e5. }
3. e5 { White begins to kick Black's knight around. } 3... Nd5 4. Nc3
{ White offers a trade of knights. } 4... e6
{ Black decides to guard the knight on d5. } 5. Nxd5 exd5 6. d4
{ White wants to severely weaken Black's pawn structure. If he takes on d4, Black will be left with tripled isolated pawns. }
6... Nc6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Qxd5
{ White has won back the pawn. Now Black has two options. } 8... d6
{ Black immediately attempts to free his light-squared bsihop. } 9. exd6 Qb6
{ Black hits the f2-pawn. } 10. Qe4+ Be6 11. Qh4 { White guards f2. } 11...
Bxd6 12. Bd3 Nb4 13. O-O Nxd3 14. cxd3
{ White has an extra pawn but Black has compensation in the bishop pair and good pawn structure. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Less Common Sicilians"]
[Black "Less Common Sicilians: Nimzowitsch Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ This quirky Sicilian is known as the Nimzowitsch Variation. Black allows White to play e5. }
3. e5 { White begins to kick Black's knight around. } 3... Nd5 4. Nc3
{ White offers a trade of knights. } 4... e6
{ Black decides to guard the knight on d5. } 5. Nxd5 exd5 6. d4
{ White wants to severely weaken Black's pawn structure. If he takes on d4, Black will be left with tripled isolated pawns. }
6... Nc6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Qxd5
{ White has won back the pawn. Now Black has two options. } 8... Qb6
{ This is the first, hitting f2. It leads to a very long forcing variation. }
9. Bc4
{ White simply ignores the threat against f2 and creates a threat of his own against f7. }
9... Bxf2+ 10. Ke2
{ This is the safest square for the king and keeps options open for the h1-rook. }
10... O-O 11. Rf1 { White is creating more threats against f7. } 11... Bc5
{ Black retreats his bishop. } 12. Ng5
{ Now White's pressure against f7 is overwhelming. } 12... Nd4+
{ White's king has to be careful however. } 13. Kd1 Ne6
{ Black blockades some of the pressure against f7. } 14. Ne4 d6
{ If Be7 instead White can play Nd6 and Black's pieces are very cramped. } 15.
exd6 { White grabs the pawn. } 15... Rd8 16. Bd3 Bxd6 { Black recaptures. } 17.
Qh5
{ White has many threats and Black will have a hard time defending. White only has to be careful about his own king. }
*

